SIMPLE: curia
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Curia
<hw>Cu"ri*a</hw> <pr>(k?"r?-?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Curle</plw> <pr>(-<?/)</pr>.</plu>
<ety>[L.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<def>One of the thirty parts into which the Roman people were divided by
Romulus.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The place of assembly of one of these
divisions.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The place where the meetings of the
senate were held; the senate house.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Middle Ages)</fld> <def>The court of a sovereign or
of a feudal lord; also; his residence or his household.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Any court of justice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The Roman See in its temporal aspects, including all
the machinery of administration; -- called also <altname>curia
Romana</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Curial</ent>⟦br⟧
